 years of neoliberal policies have displaced agriculture and logging as the principal sources of employment in northern Ontario, generating tension and unexpected alliances between tourists, residents, loggers, farmers, developers, and governmental officials over the proper uses and meanings of rural space. The repercussions of this new service-oriented countryside include increased youth outmigration, decreased full-time employment opportunities, and an ever-growing gap between the rich and the poor. A rich and detailed study based on long-term interviews and fieldwork, Permanent Weekend critically explores the catalysts and outcomes of gentrifying rural areas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgriculturexOntarioxAlmaguin Highlands. 0aAgriculturezOntariozAlmaguin Highlands. 0aGentrificationxOntarioxAlmaguin Highlands. 0aGentrificationzOntariozAlmaguin Highlands. 0aGlobalizationxOntarioxAlmaguin Highlands. 0aGlobalizationzOntariozAlmaguin Highlands. 0aRural renewalxOntarioxAlmaguin Highlands. 0aRural renewalzOntariozAlmaguin Highlands. 0aRural renewal. 0aTourismxOntarioxAlmaguin Highlands. 0aTourismzOntariozAlmaguin Highlands. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355065040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773550650423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773550650/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles